<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1949-06-12T00:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1949-06-12T00:00:00-05:00" n="414" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d414">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00119 Control (Germany)/6–1149:
                                Telegram</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of
                                        State</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                        State</gloss>, at Paris</hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#left">
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret</hi>
                                    <lb/>
                                    <gloss target="#t_niact1">
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">niact</hi>
                                    </gloss>
                                </seg>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1949-06-12T01:00:00-04:00">June
                                        12, 1949—1 a.m.</date>
                                </dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>
                                <gloss target="#t_Telac1">Telac</gloss> 77. Eyes Only for the
                                Secretary. We assume from your <gloss target="#t_Actel1">Actel</gloss> 59<note n="1" xml:id="d414fn1">
                                    <hi rend="italic">Supra.</hi>
                                </note> that you have given your approval to <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> paper<note n="2" xml:id="d414fn2">Dated June 1,
                                        <ref target="#pg_820">p. 820</ref>.</note> as now written
                                and are not asking that <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> amend
                                para 3<hi rend="italic">d</hi> along lines of <gloss target="#t_Telac1">Telac</gloss> 60.<note n="3" xml:id="d414fn3">June 6, <ref target="#pg_828">p. 828</ref>.</note> Request
                                reply to reach Dept not later than early Monday morning, if
                                possible, to meet appointment with President.</p>
                            <pb facs="0873" n="832" xml:id="pg_832"/>
                            <p>Will inform <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> and President of two
                                points covered your <gloss target="#t_Actel1">Actel</gloss> 59 and
                                intensify efforts to determine all feasible counter-measures.</p>
                            <p>Will attempt to obtain modification of <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> paper to make unmistakably clear your discretion
                                re: warning to Soviets on imposition of blockade. Have in mind an
                                additional sentence in para five reading approximately as follows:
                                “It is considered however that the desirability of making such a
                                declaration in connection with the present meeting of the <gloss target="#t_CFM1">CFM</gloss> as well as its textual content and
                                manner of presentation should be left to the discretion of the
                                Secretary of State in the light of the situation as it develops at
                                the current meeting of the <gloss target="#t_CFM1">CFM</gloss>.”<note n="4" xml:id="d414fn4">In <gloss target="#t_Actel1">Actel</gloss> 62, June 12, from Paris,
                                    not printed, Secretary <persName corresp="#p_AD1">Acheson</persName> confirmed his approval of <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> 24/2, but stated that <persName corresp="#p_WJE1">Webb</persName>’s proposed additional
                                    sentence would be desirable. (740.00119 Control
                                    (Germany)/6–1249)</note>
                            </p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <persName corresp="#p_WJE1">
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Webb</hi>
                                    </persName>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>